TypeScript is a programming language that is a superset of JavaScript. It is designed to provide optional type annotations and other features to help developers write more maintainable and scalable code. TypeScript is open source and is developed and maintained by Microsoft.

Duck typing is a concept in dynamic programming languages in which the type of an object is determined by its behavior (i.e., its methods) rather than its class or interface. In other words, if an object quacks like a duck, swims like a duck, and looks like a duck, it is a duck. Duck typing is often contrasted with static typing, in which the type of an object is determined by its class or interface.

TypeScript supports both static and duck typing. With static typing, you can specify the type of a variable or function parameter explicitly using type annotations. With duck typing, you can use the `keyof` operator to specify that a variable or function parameter must have a certain set of properties or methods. For example, you could use the following code to define a function that takes an object with a `length` property:
```
function printLength(obj: { length: number }): void {
  console.log(obj.length);
}
```
This function will work with any object that has a `length` property, regardless of its class or interface.
